Bolt Test Assignment: 2 question

Gadir Mamedov

0.1 Introduction

This document attempts to solve the following task.

  • Provide a formal definition for “TPR”. Analyse market health, provide insights and conclusions.

0.2 Tickets Per Ride (TPR) and Summary

Tickets Per Ride is a measure indicating a ratio of incoming tickets to all completed rides.

This table was done in the first part of assignment and shows calculations of TPR for both actual and predicted months. As we see, number of tickets composes around 2-3% of total rides.

I have to say that numbers provided in the table let us see “market health”. In general, we see that TPR slightly increases, while there is decrease in amount of completed rides. Ratio of uncompleted rides to completed rides in average terms equals to 0.27 which seems to be high. Almost one third of all possible rights get cancelled or uncompleted. This may cause additional problems for customer support service and other departments.

It is a bad sign that, despite the decrease in number of tickets, ratio of tickets to rides (TPR) slightly increases. And TPR Growth Rate demonstrates that there should be optimization of customer support service in place.

Dataset contains information on ride-hailing service market from 1 November 2019 to 21 January 2020, for 3 months. For this time, around 4.8 million rides was completed, while 1.8 million rides was canceled or uncompleted.

Another interesting information relates to ride distance. As may seen from summary, median amount of km is equal to 5.5. So, ride averages to 5.5 km, while 75% of all cases are not more than 9 km. However, there are clear outliers in the dataset that much higher than 9 km. For example, maximum number is around 1514 km. At the same time, dataset lacks data on 1.7 million rides.

0.4 Visualization

0.4.1 Completed and uncompleted rides

NA

Visually, amount of rides gradually decreases by February. Although, the level of uncompleted rides is waving, there is a stark increase in December. And despite the fact that number of rides falls, number of uncompleted rides seems to stay at the same level.

Everyday number of completed rides averages to 52030. Uncompleted rides mean number is 19488. If to compose a ratio, it will make 0.27. So, around 27% of all rides deem to be uncompleted in mean numbers. This may be caused by many reasons: by mistakes, users’ or drivers’ motivation and etc.

0.4.2 How many unique users and drivers there? (not counting NAs)

Unique drivers number = 24911 Unique riders number = 869596

0.5 Statistics

0.5.1 When rides get cancelled most?

This heatmap illustrates the intensity of cancellations during weekdays across time of day. As may be seen, more cancellations are observed during afternoons. Especially, there is high numbers on Sat and Fri evenings, and Sun and Sat nights. All this may reflect the intensity of rides in general.

0.5.2 Rides and hours

Amount of rides increases gradually from morning to night with slight fall during lunch hours. The same is correct for non-completed rides; although, their picks are in the monring and around 3 and 6 pm.

0.5.3 Bad ratings?

[1] 0.04479133

Considering that ratings less than 5 constitute only 4.4% of all dataset, it is interesting to look whether these rides differ or have distinct patterns that make users give them less on rating scale.

This graph shows that some drivers get a lot of non-5 rates, although their mean rate shifts righter being around 2 or 3. However, the cases when drivers systematically get 0 or 1 are insignificant.

All in all, small amount of bad rates (only 4.4%) is a positive sign for the ride-hailing market.
